Glad to see you spotted the response here in the newsgroup. I tried to
also e-mail you the answer (childs@hooked.met) and it got bounced with
an unknown user error message. BTW, just for the record when I was still
using the Promise card I ran a number of different hard drive benchmarks
with the driver in both 16bit and 32bit mode. The differences were
negligible. In fact, back before I added the 3rd and 4th hard drives and
could also use the OS/2 IBM1S506.ADD driver, I couldn't see enough
difference to matter. In fact, that is one of the neat features of this
Buslogic VLB card I replaced the Promise card with. It supports drive
linking (and mirroring if you have a need for that) and I've got my
4-540MB drives linked so that the system sees them as 2-1080MB drives.
And since the controller also does head/cylinder translation in its BIOS
I don't have any problems with the infamous 1024 cylinder limit. Boot
Manager is at the end of what is a 2096 cylinder drive (2 linked drives
of 1048 cylinders each) but because of the BIOS translation it is seen
as one 524 cylinder drive with 64 heads and 63 sectors per track.
This allows me to either use the Buslogic driver or the standard OS/2
driver. In this case, the Buslogic driver is definitely faster, both in
benchmark testing and in "look and feel".

An interesting thing here that I didn't realize at the time I did it is
that I've got one partition that actually is physically located on two
different hard drives. Geez, what will they think of next <grin>??

Anyway, if you're going to be looking for a replacement controller, you
may want to give some consideration to the Buslogic line of caching
controller. They make ISA, VLB and PCI versions that all have the same
basic feature set. The only "bad" feature about them that I've
discovered is that their BIOS translation will only handle IDE drives up
to 4GIG in size (seen many of those lately...grin) but that can be
remedied with an updated BIOS someday when IDE drives that large finally
show up.

